<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Sesuvium</i> <i>verrucosum</i> is dominant or co-dominant in the herbaceous layer with <i>Chenopodium</i> <i>chenopodioides</i>, <i>Cotula</i> <i>coronopifolia</i>, <i>Distichlis</i> <i>spicata</i>, <i>Heliotropium</i> <i>curassavicum</i>, <i>Lolium</i> <i>perenne</i>, <i>Rumex</i> <i>crispus</i>, <i>Rumex</i> <i>pulcher</i>, <i>Salicornia</i> <i>bigelovii</i>, <i>Sarcocornia</i> <i>pacifica</i> and <i>Spergularia</i> <i>marina</i>. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Herbs < 1 m; cover is open to intermittent. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Sesuvium verrucosum</i> > 50% relative cover in the herbaceous layer (Keeler-Wolf and Vaghti 2000).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Moist or seasonally dry alkaline flats; margins of usually saline or alkaline habitats, including coastal wetlands, vernal pools, and desert playas. Soils are usually clay. The USFWS Wetland Inventory (1996 national list) recognizes <i>Sesuvium verrucosum</i> as a FACW plant. </div>
</div>

        
