    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        
            <p>The range of <i>Sesuvium verrucosum</i> includes the Central California Coast (261A), Central California Coast Ranges (M262A), Mono (341D), Southeastern Great Basin (341F), Southern California Coast (261B), and Southern California Mountains and Valleys (M262B).</p>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Great Valley</b> (262Ai-l, Aq, At, Av-w, Ay). Stands at Suisun Marsh (Baye et al. 2000, Keeler-Wolf and Vaghti 2000) characterize the alliance. Stands also occur in the Kern National Wildlife Refuge and other alkaline wetlands in the southern San Joaquin Valley.</li>
        
            <li><b>Mojave Desert</b> (322Ag-h). Mixed stands of <i>S. verrucousum</i> and <i>Heliotropium curassavicum</i> occupy seasonally wet, alkali sinks in the Mojave River drainage (Courtois 1984).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Stands in Suisun Marsh are frequently the result of colonization after mechanical scraping. Stands are phenologically later than stands of <i>Cotula coronopifolia, </i>which may occupy the same area earlier in the season. Wildlife relishes the seeds of <i>Sesuvium verrucosum</i>; local managers foster its growth by making depressions to create long inundation pools after winter flooding. Plants germinate in mid to late spring and mature into large, dense mats by midsummer, when the pool bottoms are dry and cracked. </div>
</div>

    

    

